2500|$|Two centuries after Jonathan Edwards {{sought a}} {{link with the}} divine in the {{beautiful}} clarity of things, William Carlos Williams wrote in introducing his long poem Paterson that [...] "for the poet there are no ideas but in things." [...] No ideas but in things. The American artist, first born into a continent without museums and art schools, took Nature as his only instructor, and things as his principal study. A bias toward the empirical, toward the evidential object in the numinous fullness of its being, leads to a certain <b>lininess,</b> as the artist intently maps the visible in a New World that feels surrounded by chaos and emptiness.|$|E

